,Not Recommended,266490,15260276,"Posted: 7 April, 2015",all,caelumsixsmith,"AN EXCITING JOURNEY ABOUT... COLLECTING FLOWERS?The concept seems rather boring, but put some quirky characters, interesting world design and beautiful visuals on the mix and thus is bornLili: Child of Geos! A mixture ofYume NikkiandFEZon a 3D environment, Lili's journey to complete her degree in something quite close to botany is not only a banquet for the sight, but also an entertaining non-violent alternative to not-always-so-subtle gaming references and somewhat-intelligent humor. However, as most indie games that try to inovate, the title has remarkable flaws or raw concepts.The story is not impressive or captivating, but the funny and varied cast of characters sure compensate to what could be a dull, uninspiring experience with a cute message that didn't stick because the road to it was so ""meh"". Although the game has no voice overs (despite a few heys, yep and ""SOUP, SOUP SOUP!""), the dialogues flow smoothly, soon making you feel like you know the pers... no... construct you're talking to.Gameplay-wise, there's not much on store. First, there is no such thing as full controller support (if you want to play with a controller, that is) as the store page implies. This is actually apartial controller supportwhere you'll get to use the analog sticks to move the mouse cursor on menus and get XBox controller inputs only during the ""fights"", making you get used to how 1, 2 and 3 translate on an XBox controller or simply use the keyboard when those item slots are necessary. After the early struggle, you'll soon find that the only interesting thing about the game is its ""unique"" way to deal with enemies -- which is actually a far more simplistic and fast pacedShadow of the Colossus, but with smaller enemies. Simply put, you jump on their backs and try to cope with a swarm of commands indicating where you can pull flowers, thorns or bombs, carefully not to dry the ""grip"" matter as that will make you fall off the enemy. With a decent score you get to collect that enemy's unique mask and learn about it. Other than that, running (walking is exclusive to houses), collecting flowers and the few RPG elements are clunky and raw. There was a lot of room for improvement, but clearly the developers wanted to seel a gorgeous game with that one fresh feature that you won't even get to play that much.Speaking of features, content is another thingLili: Child of Geoslacks. There are no puzzles at all, unless the game giving you the answer to stepping on buttons is considered a puzzle now days. For an exploration game with no actual combat, puzzles could make the experience far more enjoyable! The world layout is entertaining, but soon falls flat as the areas are pretty much narrowed corridors without much places to go. No no dear, you cannot jump or swim to anywhere you want to explore -- not that there are many places you think you could jump to anyways. You won't have to work much to get the god-mode items (e.g. the skeleton key and the treasure map), either, so instead of having the slightest hint of challenge on a casual exploration game (because even though it's casual, doesn't mean it can't be challenging), you can just keep running, collecting flowers, kicking vases and collecting flowers from the back of spirits. As for the outfits and hats, considering how short the game is and how useless they are (only there for cosmetics and eventually some lore relevance), there could be a larger variety -- like letting us use the Mario collectable hat as an actual hat instead of hinting on a reference-NPC that doesn't even exist.Pros:Gorgeous graphicsRuns smoothly at highest settings on a medium rigInteresting designsQuirky, funny charactersNice musicSome subtle and funny references to the gaming worldAn exploration game with few RPG elements and a weak focus on flower collectingCons:Partial controller support instead of fullGameplay feels clunky at timesNo puzzlesThe only inovative mechanic is uninteresting and might become a burden if you're not a fast catcherThere could be more hatsThere could be more petsFlowers could be more relevantThere could be more items and shopsSome game references feel stupid (if I can call the Portal 2 thing a reference)Extremely linear considering what an open world can offerExtremely short considering the potential it had (you can clear the game and most of the achievments on a single day, maybe two if you decide to take on the 1000 vases and flowers)All in all,Lili: Child of Geosis a funny one-time experience with a lot of wasted potential. Gorgeous graphics and funny characters, but poor controller support (considering the developers promised full support), lack of content and short playthrough. Doesn't justify the full price, but worth checking out at a nice discount."
