,Recommended,266490,10071812,"Posted: 10 May, 2014",all,Vorrtexx,"Having sailed to the island of Geos for a school project, you are tasked with gathering up rare flowers to report back to your professor.However something is not quite right on the island and you soon discover that the constructs (creatures created from wood) are slaves to their masters; the spirits and their Mayor.You decide to unshackle the local natives from their forced labour by doing them favours in exchange for flowers and other rare items. The island is full of life, its characters witty and charming where I couldn't help but laugh at some of the dialogue that was exchanged.Where its similarities between Zelda lie are based around the Islands and town hubs which you would find in a Zelda game.Imagine taking those areas from Wind Waker and putting them on this island. The exchange of dialogue is something you would find straight out of a Zelda game. Don't expect voiced characters but instead small sound bites like ""Hi"", ""Bye"" and other gasps throughout the dialogue.Don't expect to be crawling dungeons and having a boss fight. This is not where its comparison with Zelda lies.There are lots of Easter eggs to discover throughout the Island in treasure chests that reference some classic Nintendo games. Another character will throw some Video game trivia at you, asking you to guess what game it is referencing. ""Praise the Sun"".Hats can be found in treasure chests and by doing services for the locals. Masks can be unlocked by beating Spirits.As a collectathon it has similarities to Banjo-Kazooie. Achievements are awarded for smashing pots, finding treasure and picking flowers.Fighting in the game is composed of hopping on the back of a Spirit and attempting to pluck flowers from its back while they put obstacles in your way such as thorns and bombs.There is currently only partial controller support, with the mouse really only needed for the Spirit fights and closing menus. I'm sure adding a button binding for B to close menus will soon come in an update. I am unsure how Battling the spirits with a controller will work though. Its interaction seems more suited to a mouse or tablet, although the developers have said in the forum they are working on full controller support.Overall I would highly recommend the game if you grew up playing Nintendo games like Zelda, Banjo or Mario.While there is no platforming involved, a mixture of all these games can be found in Lili: Child of Geos.The graphics are just downright gorgeous and full of colour. The music sounds like something that belongs in a Zelda game. It's a casual adventure game with some very basic RPG elements that involve levelling up your Speed, Grip and Stealth.I haven't played a game like this since the N64."
