,Not Recommended,266490,13245436,"Posted: 5 December, 2014",all,Lintire,"Lili: Child of Geos is a game with massive potential that would've been excellent if it were actually made for the PC, and worst of all it's not even the developer's fault.Seeing this game in the Steam Store, the first thoughts to come to mind were ""This looks fantastic"" and ""Why haven't I heard of this before""? Unfortunately the answer was evident in about 10 minutes. This is a mobile port - a fantastic looking one that trumps most indie games made for the PC proper in terms of looks, but a mobile port nonetheless and that permeates the game to its core.This game is obviously a labour of love and it shows. But that it's also a mobile game utterly annihilates all of its positives - there's a ""but"" for each and every one.•Every inch of the world looks fantastic, but you can't interact with it beyond walking around it.•All of the levels are utterly distinct, but there's only four of them and they take 20 minutes to beat.•The characters are well written and distinctly funny, but you never get more than half a dozen lines out of even the most prominent ones.•There's sidequests and optional content, but they're all threadbare.•Design is solid all around, but assets are reused to a comical degree - I had trouble telling NPCs apart.Threadbare describes the game as a whole. Combat altering inventory items? Great idea. There's three of them and they're thrown at you, though. Stat increase system? Great idea. Shallow as a puddle, though. Climactic mid-sequence about abandoning previous life choices? Great idea. It consists of three and a half lines of dialogue either way and falls completely flat though.Worst case is the combat (or ""combat"", but there's enough high-octane explosives involved that I think you can safely ignore the whole nonviolent billing) - you perform the same unchanging minigame twenty or so times and then the game is over. Fifty-five if you're aiming for completionist.For a mobile game these are all more than excusable. Hell, I've no doubt that had I played this on a mobile device it would rank up there with the best; Dead Space iOS and Infinity Blade. But I didn't, and for a PC game, to put it lightly, it kicks it straight in the balls. Right in there. And it isn't the developers' fault. But that's just how it is.At it's best Lili: Child of Geos is an exercise in frustration at lost potential the likes of which I haven't felt since Crash Twinsanity.Even though I wouldn't actually recommend this to anyone, maybe just buy it anyway. Support the developers. I want to see another game from them. Built from the ground up for PC this time.Also, gamepad support is kind of lacking and the video game references get a little shoehorned at times."
