,Recommended,266490,14330358,"Posted: 4 February, 2015",all,80s Cartoon Character,"Lili: Child of Geos is a short little adventure game with a combat system that's basically a mini puzzle game. The premise is that Lili has arrived on a mysterious island in order to study plants. She discovers a society run by Spirits who build wooden people called Contructs to do their bidding. Her mission then becomes to help the Constructs find freedom by defeating the Spirits. To defeat the Spirits, she has to pull flowers out of their backs. If you're using a keyboard and mouse, you'll use the mouse pointer to manually pick out flowers whilst avoiding thorns. If using a controller, you'll use corresponding buttons (A, X, B, and Y if you're using an Xbox 360 controller).Inbetween fights, you'll explore the land of Geos, opening chests and doors and doing various side tasks for the local residents. As you progress, you'll gain points to improve your ability to grip onto Spirits, run, and approach Spirits without them noticing you (these are listed as Grip, Run, and Sneak respectively). This is how they qualify that whole ""RPG hybrid"" bit.The game will take you a few hours to complete if you do every sidequests (and by ""a few"" I mean less than 3 or 4 depending on how well you can find flowers and avoid falling off Spirits) so the $20 price tag may not be worth it unless you can find replay value in defeating straggling Spirits, rematching old ones for a higher score, or venturing into a harder difficulty.If I had to recommend this game, it probably wouldn't be to fans of Zelda, Broken Age, or Psychonauts (although there are 3 or 4 Zelda references that might bore you), but I'd be lying if I said it wasn't enjoyable. Still, the short length and the shortage of explorable areas keep the game from being the Zelda-esque adventure it strives to be.So ultimately, can I recommend this game? I want to say, ""No,"" but I had fun with it, so I'll begrudgingly press the ""Yes"" button alongside a precaution to wait for a sale."
76561198002864416,Recommended,266490,14242593,"Posted: 30 January, 2015",all,The Morgue,"Lili is a sweet and enjoyable little family game, hampered by a lack of polish and a rather threadbare plot.You play Lili, of course, a young student who arrives on a thought-to-be deserted island in search of flowers.  Once there, you discover that a race of beings called Constructs are working as slaves for vicious little critters called Spirits.  Naturally, you'll battle the Spirits, free the Constructs, do a little soul-searching, and save the day.The gameplay is charming, but fairly limited.  You'll walk around, talk to people, do fetch quests, and fight Spirits in what are essentially QTE mini-games.  You jump on their backs and pluck all of their flowers out, avoiding thorns and shedding bombs as you go.  Defeated Spirits merely run off in a huff; everything is very non-violent and kid appropriate.  There's also a gambling mini-game that is fun for a few spins.Sadly, there isn't much story to tie it all together.  It's clear that the evil Mayor will be the Big Bad from the get-go, so not much mystery there.  Lili's only real drama is whether or not to abandon the Constructs to turn in her project on time, and I doubt anyone will be very confounded on which path to choose.  Lili will also exchange letters with her professor that hint at some deeper family trauma at play, but it's only brought up at the very end of the game and nothing much is said of it.  Exploring that a little further might have added some real heart to the game and made it feel a bit more substantial.Of course, many of the game's shortcomings can be traced to its origins as a smartphone app, with an emphasis on sharp graphics and simplistic gameplay.  Make no mistake, the game is quite beautiful, but the transition from app to Steam product was less than ideal.  The game feels a bit unpolished all over, and the achievements are a total mess - some are bugged, others pop up erroneously, and many are tedious grinds which are completely inessential to clearing the game.  The game was perfectly playable on my end and didn't crash, but the whole thing felt rushed.And yet, with all that said, I'll give the game a mild thumbs up.  It's nice to see a family appropriate game on Steam, especially with a female protagonist.  It looks great, has pleasant tunes, and the writing can be quite funny in places.  You can tell that the adult writers were slipping in a ton of gags to either amuse themselves or any parents nearby.  It all goes down easy and most people will get a few hours of fun out of it.  That said, I got the game for 85% off - I wouldn't pay anything close to the base price of $20 for it.  Something in the $5 range is more appropriate."
